And it's like...

19:10.107 --> 19:12.724
What the fuck
am I supposed to do now?

19:12.902 --> 19:15.485
I mean, I can't get both.

19:15.696 --> 19:16.696
Hey.

19:18.491 --> 19:21.279
It's just
going to take some time.

19:21.494 --> 19:23.656
How long have
you been coming here?

19:23.871 --> 19:25.453
15 years.

19:32.922 --> 19:34.458
I would've gone to Paris.

19:34.632 --> 19:38.421
No, she remodels.

19:39.762 --> 19:41.845
[Katie] Nate?

19:43.474 --> 19:44.806
Nate Brown.

19:45.976 --> 19:50.095
It's Katie, Katie Franco,

19:51.982 --> 19:55.066
- used to be Hamilton.
- Oh, Katie.

19:55.277 --> 19:58.270
Katie, hi!

19:58.489 --> 20:00.196
What the hell happened to you?

20:00.408 --> 20:02.070
I'll take that as a compliment.

20:02.284 --> 20:06.654
And you look
like you always did.

20:06.872 --> 20:10.582
Really? Because half of me
is divorcing the other half.

20:10.793 --> 20:13.752
- Aw, you too?
- M-hm.

20:16.048 --> 20:18.165
So, what are you up to now?

20:18.384 --> 20:21.673
You still helping the betrothed
march to their emotional death?

20:21.887 --> 20:23.879
- God, no.
- Really?

20:24.098 --> 20:26.385
That... that was your life.
You lived for it.

20:26.600 --> 20:30.719
No, I had what could
be innocently described

20:30.938 --> 20:34.306
as a complete fucking meltdown
where I lost my cool on a customer

20:34.525 --> 20:36.892
to the point where
they called off the engagement.

20:37.945 --> 20:39.652
Probably good you quit.

20:39.864 --> 20:42.277
Are you kidding? It was
like the best day of my life.

20:42.491 --> 20:45.984
I... suddenly felt
empowered and inspired

20:46.203 --> 20:49.412
and it allowed me to shed the past
and take hold of my own life.

20:52.626 --> 20:55.790
I thought from that moment on

20:56.005 --> 20:58.167
of my breakup as my wakeup,

20:58.382 --> 21:02.251
as the moment in my life when
I said, "I am my own person.

21:02.470 --> 21:06.305
I'm not just half of Katie
and Chuck. I'm Katie Franco."

21:06.515 --> 21:10.885
and the fun of the single thing is starting
over. Don't commiserate, celebrate.

21:11.103 --> 21:13.516
- What is there to celebrate?
- You.

21:13.731 --> 21:15.723
Your newfound freedom,
your independence.

21:15.941 --> 21:19.434
- The new life you're about to embark on.
- Celebrate being single?

21:22.782 --> 21:25.240
My... my marriage
was everything to me.

21:25.451 --> 21:29.161
Operative word: <i>Was.</i>
You got to start living in the now.

21:29.371 --> 21:31.158
- Fuck the past.
- Fuck the past?

21:31.332 --> 21:33.198
- Seize your future.
- Carpe diem?

21:33.417 --> 21:36.330
Listen, you guys
planned a wedding, right?

21:37.421 --> 21:40.255
That was just one big party.
Why don't you throw another one?

21:41.300 --> 21:42.916
I don't know,
I guess I could try.

21:45.137 --> 21:48.257
I just don't know if I could pull it off.
Seems like a lot to celebrate just <i>moi.</i>

21:48.974 --> 21:51.307
Who else would
you rather celebrate?

21:54.355 --> 21:57.473
Well, listen.
Call me if you need me.

21:57.691 --> 21:59.432
I'm back to being an accountant.

21:59.652 --> 22:02.269
Taxes after
a divorce can be a bit tricky.

22:07.993 --> 22:11.077
[typing on keyboard]

22:11.288 --> 22:12.288
Cele...

22:12.331 --> 22:13.947
...brate.

22:19.713 --> 22:23.332
7:00 p.m.

22:32.309 --> 22:34.346
[Susan]
This is so out of character.

22:34.562 --> 22:37.555
I'm honestly surprised
he came up with it himself.

22:37.773 --> 22:39.730
Really? You think?

22:39.942 --> 22:44.653
If that was my ex-husband,
I... I would sabotage the party

22:44.822 --> 22:48.406
and make a complete ass out of him in
front of all of his loser friends.

22:49.994 --> 22:51.781
Hypothetically
speaking, you know.

22:51.996 --> 22:56.036
[laughs] Jan loves
her little hypotheticals.

22:56.250 --> 22:58.833
- You know, I just... Throwing a party is hard.
- It's tough.

22:59.044 --> 23:03.664
It's not just buying a six-pack
and serving some onion dip,

23:03.883 --> 23:06.091
it's... it's a lot more,
you know.

23:06.302 --> 23:09.545
I always planned who's
coming and what we would serve

23:09.763 --> 23:11.675
and where they
would sit, you know?

23:13.142 --> 23:15.099
I always made him
feel like he was involved.

23:15.311 --> 23:18.304
Yeah, he always had those amazing
syrupy sweet and spicy ribs.

23:18.522 --> 23:23.517
- Seriously? It was seriously not syrupy.
- Misspoke.

23:23.736 --> 23:29.198
And if I hadn't added white pepper to
the rub, it would have been bland.

23:29.408 --> 23:33.823
And if I didn't constantly baste the ribs,
it would've burned.

23:34.038 --> 23:38.829
If I didn't serve merlot, he
would've served chardonnay, so.

23:39.043 --> 23:42.627
- That would not have gone...
- You can't do that.

23:42.838 --> 23:44.579
After the term alimony?

23:46.008 --> 23:48.671
Permanent alimony.

23:50.012 --> 23:55.428
Her pension contribution
entitlement, her car insurance.

23:56.810 --> 23:58.767
Her healthcare coverage.

23:59.730 --> 24:02.598
I see 17% of my salary.

24:03.776 --> 24:06.268
One-seven.

24:09.114 --> 24:11.527
No wonder I feel 83% like shit.

24:14.787 --> 24:16.119
The irony?

24:18.207 --> 24:22.872
Before our first date,
I dreamed of fucking her

24:26.090 --> 24:28.332
and now she's fucking me.

24:28.550 --> 24:30.086
Right up the ass.

24:33.597 --> 24:37.216
Okay. Uh...

24:37.434 --> 24:40.973
Anyone else have
anything they'd like to add?

24:42.690 --> 24:44.352
I have something.

24:45.985 --> 24:47.521
Uhm...

24:49.571 --> 24:53.440
I was actually trying to think about
this divorce thing in a whole new way.

24:54.535 --> 24:56.492
So instead of
feeling like shit about it,

24:56.704 --> 24:59.822
I decided why not have a party?

25:00.040 --> 25:05.877
I'm... I'm sorry,
why not have a what?

25:06.088 --> 25:07.499
A divorce party.

25:08.590 --> 25:10.547
Nate...

25:10.759 --> 25:15.174
I... I think
that might be misdirecting

25:15.389 --> 25:17.756
some of the pain
that you're feeling.

25:17.975 --> 25:21.685
Yeah, why would
you want to do that?

25:21.895 --> 25:24.478
I mean, you could think
about it any way you want,

25:24.690 --> 25:28.274
but you'd still be broadcasting
your failure to the world.

25:28.485 --> 25:32.354
We come in here to share
our lives with each other,

25:32.573 --> 25:34.735
but we keep it in this room.

25:34.908 --> 25:37.400
You want to share your
misery with the world?

25:37.619 --> 25:42.114
Fine, but for me,
I... I'd rather be safe in here,

25:43.042 --> 25:45.580
than deal with
what's going on out there.

25:47.421 --> 25:51.290
[radio playing]

25:53.093 --> 25:55.585
I need to understand how I,

25:55.804 --> 25:58.467
a guy that I think
is pretty normal, not offensive,

25:58.682 --> 26:03.097
only rarely loses his temper in public,
only has one guest attending his party.

26:03.270 --> 26:05.353
- What party?
- The divorce party.

26:07.066 --> 26:09.353
The one that you RSVP'd to?

26:09.568 --> 26:11.730
Oh, yeah. Here it is.

26:12.821 --> 26:16.690
Well, first of all,
I RSVP yes to every invite.

26:16.909 --> 26:19.572
It doesn't mean I'm going, it
means that you think I'm going.

26:19.787 --> 26:23.622
So for the next week, if I see you at spin
class, you don't think I'm lame for saying no.

26:24.666 --> 26:27.124
Then, about an hour
before the party starts,

26:27.336 --> 26:30.044
I send you an email with
something along the lines of,

26:30.255 --> 26:33.248
"Oh my God,
I'm so sorry I can't make it.

26:33.467 --> 26:35.208
But do a sh <i>o</i> t f <i>o</i> r me.
Love you. Katie."

26:36.553 --> 26:38.215
So you weren't coming either?

26:38.388 --> 26:39.799
No, of course not.

26:41.350 --> 26:44.434
- Okay.
- Listen, Nate. I don't know what to tell you.

26:44.645 --> 26:48.013
You decided to throw a party and now you're
realizing that without your marriage,

26:48.232 --> 26:50.315
no one feels obligated
to show up just for you.

26:50.526 --> 26:51.607
Why not?

26:53.529 --> 26:56.290
Because you used to be half of something
and now you're all of nothing.

26:57.366 --> 26:59.904
- Don't you think that's kind of your fault?
- Oh, my fault?

27:00.077 --> 27:03.286
Yeah. I mean, you gave me the whole,
"Don't commiserate, celebrate" speech.

27:03.497 --> 27:05.989
Nate, please.
Look at your invite.

27:06.208 --> 27:09.827
Chips and dip at the Savannah Inn
Express isn't a party, it's pathetic.

27:11.505 --> 27:15.124
- I got the Double Deluxe Suite.
- Nate, if you want to have a successful divorce party,

27:15.342 --> 27:17.299
- y <i>o</i> u got to treat this as if...
- As if what?

27:17.511 --> 27:20.424
As if it was
as important as your wedding.

27:20.639 --> 27:24.553
Okay. Look, if I had 30 grand to
spend, I'd throw something cool,

27:24.768 --> 27:27.049
- but I don't have that kind of money.
- Are you telling me

27:27.104 --> 27:30.017
your new life is only worth a bag of
tortilla chips and a jar of salsa?

27:30.232 --> 27:31.973
Because that's what I'm hearing.

27:32.192 --> 27:35.481
Okay, think about it. If you
were getting married somehow,

27:35.696 --> 27:40.282
you and your over-eager bride would find the
money to flaunt your new life together, right?

27:45.080 --> 27:47.242
Why don't you throw it for me?

27:47.457 --> 27:48.789
What?

27:49.001 --> 27:51.243
I mean, you love doing that.
You lived for it.

27:51.461 --> 27:52.461
No.

27:53.505 --> 27:56.248
What I lived for
was a feeling, you know?

27:58.302 --> 28:01.761
The rush of making a memory that could
maybe carry somebody through a lifetime.

28:02.681 --> 28:03.681
Like...

28:05.309 --> 28:07.551
I was creating a piece of art,

28:09.438 --> 28:11.100
and I was the artist,

28:14.526 --> 28:16.609
but that was the past.

28:16.778 --> 28:19.065
Your specialty was sending
people off into the world,

28:19.281 --> 28:21.273
with the memory
of the best day of their lives.

28:22.534 --> 28:24.776
Help me have
a new best day of my life.

28:25.787 --> 28:27.323
Make me a work of art.

28:28.624 --> 28:29.740
Please?

28:37.591 --> 28:41.050
Okay. If you can find
the money to pay my full fee

28:41.261 --> 28:44.174
and allow me to plan something
with the bells and whistles

28:44.389 --> 28:48.224
that keeps my former reputation
intact, then I'll do it.

28:51.438 --> 28:53.020
Okay.

28:54.483 --> 28:57.100
[optimistic music playing]

29:12.042 --> 29:15.456
[door opens and closes]

29:25.847 --> 29:29.466
- [Susan] Okay, are we good?
- [Nick] Okay. All right.

29:29.685 --> 29:30.892
Look at that body.

29:35.649 --> 29:41.486
[Nick moaning] Fuck, yeah.

29:42.614 --> 29:46.278
[Nick] Ooh, yeah. Come on, baby.

29:47.828 --> 29:51.367
[grunts and laughs]

29:51.581 --> 29:54.619
Oh, Jesus Christ already!

29:54.835 --> 29:57.669
Nate! What the hell
are you doing here?

29:57.879 --> 30:00.542
Oh, my God.
I thought you'd be at work.

30:00.757 --> 30:04.216
There must be some reason, some urgent
need that absolutely could not wait.

30:04.428 --> 30:07.091
- Well, I need my tennis shoes.
- Your tennis shoes?

30:07.306 --> 30:09.844
Yeah, I looked in the closet and
on the shoe rack and I just...

30:10.058 --> 30:14.177
Yeah, dude, yeah
right behind my ab-roller.

30:14.396 --> 30:17.013
Yeah.

30:17.232 --> 30:20.350
Yes, little guy, huh?

30:20.569 --> 30:22.481
He's...

30:24.197 --> 30:27.156
Size eight and a half, right?

30:28.869 --> 30:31.657
Nine and a half. [clears throat]

30:31.872 --> 30:36.242
Yeah, thank you. Okay.

30:37.627 --> 30:42.088
[Nate] <i>There I was standing in front of my
soon to be ex and her buck naked boyfriend</i>

30:42.299 --> 30:46.885
<i>and it was clear,
the ring meant absolutely nothing to her.</i>

30:47.095 --> 30:51.806
It was like she was void of that gush of
emotion that she had when I proposed.

30:51.975 --> 30:57.391
I spent weeks, months even
researching the stupid four C's:

30:57.606 --> 31:00.349
cut, color, clarity, and carat.

31:00.567 --> 31:04.652
I organized a flash mob
for the perfect proposal.

31:04.863 --> 31:07.196
I even hired dancers
to present the ring.

31:08.617 --> 31:12.452
I mean, the fucking absurdity of
this invented tradition where men

31:12.662 --> 31:14.654
have to bust their ass

31:15.791 --> 31:19.455
and spend three months salary just
to express their undying devotion.

31:21.588 --> 31:23.955
I mean, when
the hell did that start?

31:24.174 --> 31:25.961
When men were stupid
enough to fall for it.

31:27.302 --> 31:29.635
I don't know, maybe
I should just give it back.

31:29.846 --> 31:33.931
Well, the courts look at an engagement
ring as a promise of a marriage,

31:34.142 --> 31:37.635
and that the bride fulfills that promise,
and your ex certainly did.

31:37.854 --> 31:40.722
It's supposedly hers,
free and clear.

31:40.941 --> 31:43.979
- You think I should return it?
- Hell no, it's a bullshit law.

31:44.194 --> 31:49.610
Hock that ring and you get as much
money for it as you can, fuck her.

31:54.996 --> 31:58.660
This is the Bridal Bible,
all my girls used to get one.

31:58.875 --> 32:04.212
It's the "how to" for the "I do" even if
we're celebrating the death of your marriage.

32:05.799 --> 32:09.759
Since you've been lost in the
delusional fairy tale of marriage,

32:09.970 --> 32:12.758
how about
something truly romantic?

32:12.973 --> 32:15.807
Maybe even a mask party where
we reveal the new Nate Brown.

32:16.017 --> 32:17.599
Hm? What do you think?

32:20.230 --> 32:21.311
[Nate] I don't know.

32:27.112 --> 32:32.153
How about this, you've got a sweeping
view of the water, what's not to love?

32:32.367 --> 32:35.610
And we could even do maybe like,
a little spiritual cleansing in the river.

32:40.041 --> 32:41.202
I don't know.

32:46.840 --> 32:51.926
I thought this could be the perfect place
to be loud and proud about your new life.

32:53.430 --> 32:54.430
What do you think?

32:56.183 --> 32:57.390
Maybe.

33:00.270 --> 33:03.684
What about something
exotic like Indian food?

33:03.899 --> 33:06.562
- We don't like Indian.
- What do you mean <i>we</i> ?

33:07.486 --> 33:09.318
I mean me.

33:12.115 --> 33:14.778
- [Nick] That is bitching.
- [Susan] Yeah, and if I serve that,

33:14.993 --> 33:16.780
everyone's going
to think I'm a huge a bitch.

33:16.995 --> 33:21.456
Maybe, it's cushy.

33:21.666 --> 33:23.578
It's cringe-worthy.

33:23.752 --> 33:27.086
I don't want people to think that I
have all of this pent-up emotions,

33:27.297 --> 33:30.005
this bitter pill that
I'm forcing them to swallow.

33:30.217 --> 33:31.674
This looks like
a Halloween cake.

33:31.885 --> 33:34.093
Besides, no one even
likes white icing, do they?

33:34.304 --> 33:37.297
I mean, it's just a cake.

33:39.684 --> 33:41.550
I set the seating at a 100.

33:41.770 --> 33:45.935
We can always adjust up if we
need to or down for that matter.

33:46.149 --> 33:50.109
I don't understand why we're working on a
seating chart when I don't have any guests yet.

33:50.320 --> 33:54.781
- That's exactly my point.
- And it's valid, but I don't have anyone to invite.

33:55.784 --> 33:59.573
All of my so-called friends were just
bodies that would come over two by two

33:59.788 --> 34:01.529
for bland wine
and safe conversation.

34:01.748 --> 34:03.034
Trust me, I remember that.

34:03.250 --> 34:05.663
Your revolving list
of couple friend guests.

34:05.877 --> 34:07.837
Listen, it doesn't matter,
because I'm pretty sure

34:08.004 --> 34:10.212
those people are going
to go to Susan's party anyways.

34:11.925 --> 34:15.543
Of course, she's having a party.
She lives for those things.

34:16.513 --> 34:22.350
Exactly, so why don't you let her live
her life while you go define yours.

34:24.187 --> 34:26.725
Go find some people
you actually want to be around.

34:27.857 --> 34:30.065
[Colin] 39 trees, 39.

34:30.277 --> 34:32.268
It's got to have greenery.

34:35.949 --> 34:38.315
- Hey, guys.
- Hey, man.

34:38.534 --> 34:40.822
Just wanted to see what you
guys were up to this weekend.

34:41.036 --> 34:45.452
See If you wanted to have some brewskis
or tease some tail or something.

34:45.667 --> 34:49.502
I'm sorry, tease some tail?

34:49.713 --> 34:52.456
Yeah, you know,
go out and just...

34:52.674 --> 34:55.007
Everything okay?

34:55.217 --> 34:57.210
Yeah, yeah,
everything's fine. I'm fine.

34:57.429 --> 34:59.967
- Well, better than fine.
- You don't have to lie.

35:01.057 --> 35:03.390
I'm not, lie about what?

35:03.602 --> 35:06.470
A guy's wife who's in my fantasy league,
who also take yoga with Jan,

35:06.688 --> 35:10.932
who apparently attends your dinner parties,
told us that Susan kicked you out.

35:11.151 --> 35:13.359
Why weren't we invited
to those dinner parties?

35:13.570 --> 35:16.734
We're just... We're
working through some issues.

35:16.948 --> 35:19.031
- She's divorcing you.
- That is one of the issues.

35:19.242 --> 35:21.282
Look, those dinner parties
were boring. I was bored.

35:21.369 --> 35:23.531
- You guys would have been bored.
- All right, look,

35:23.747 --> 35:26.285
we see through
your little charade here.

35:26.499 --> 35:28.832
Clearly, everything isn't
hunky dory in Brown manor

35:29.044 --> 35:32.082
and now that there's no Susan,
I'd say you're a little

35:33.465 --> 35:34.922
desperate to hang out with us.

35:35.133 --> 35:37.841
Desperate? I'm not desperate.

35:39.471 --> 35:43.135
- What do you think?
- We're going to that thing this weekend.

35:43.350 --> 35:48.812
[whispering]

35:48.980 --> 35:51.063
- All right, look. Here's the deal, dude, no.
- No.

35:51.274 --> 35:53.561
- Not in this condition.
- What condition?

35:53.777 --> 35:56.645
You're like a caged man
in the zoo of life,

35:56.863 --> 36:00.106
a sad little Panda cub that's
been protected behind bars,

36:00.325 --> 36:04.740
suckling milk from your mother's tits
and now, you don't have a mommy anymore.

36:04.954 --> 36:09.164
Trust us, this is for your own safety.
If we put you into the wild, you'd be killed.

36:09.376 --> 36:11.868
I can survive in the wild, okay?

36:12.087 --> 36:13.328
I can be a tiger.

36:14.464 --> 36:15.750
I can kill.

36:22.013 --> 36:23.470
- Seth. Hey, man.
- Good to see you.

36:23.682 --> 36:25.719
Heidi, what's up, baby?
Looking good.

36:25.934 --> 36:28.472
- Hey.
- Yo.

36:32.524 --> 36:33.685
Alright.

36:36.820 --> 36:39.528
Hi, just be cool, right? Mingle.

36:48.623 --> 36:51.411
[background chattering]

36:55.588 --> 37:00.253
It's good to be out, you know,
on my own, solo, kicking it.

37:01.344 --> 37:04.198
Not having to worry about what time I get
home tonight, so I can make some stupid

37:04.222 --> 37:06.885
brunch plans in the morning,
do you know what that's like?

37:07.100 --> 37:10.639
I mean, dude,
I spent so much time

37:10.854 --> 37:14.143
worrying about
Susan this, Susan that.

37:14.357 --> 37:18.192
Trying to keep her happy for her to turn
around one day and tell me that she's unhappy.

37:19.279 --> 37:20.815
What the fuck is up with that?

37:21.990 --> 37:24.482
[cheering]

37:25.243 --> 37:28.597
I mean it's okay. At least I'm not one of those
guys that has to talk about it all the time.

37:28.621 --> 37:29.987
- You know?
- All right, baby.

37:30.206 --> 37:32.573
Your turn to drink,
let's go, okay.

37:32.792 --> 37:35.626
Chug, chug, chug.

37:35.837 --> 37:39.421
[all] Chug, chug, chug.

37:39.632 --> 37:42.966
- [cheers]
- Chug.

37:43.178 --> 37:45.761
I got you. [laughs]

37:51.019 --> 37:54.683
Chad, badass rad Chad.

37:56.441 --> 37:58.728
What's up, motherfucker?

38:01.571 --> 38:06.862
[sighs] Hey dude,

38:07.076 --> 38:08.692
all kidding aside,

38:08.912 --> 38:11.996
- you're a really awesome guy, man.
- Yeah. Yeah.

38:12.207 --> 38:15.826
- Cool, man.
- I love you, buddy.

38:17.670 --> 38:19.161
